Turkey signed an Association Agreement with the EC in 1963 (suspended between 1980 and 1986 following a military coup), and applied for EU membership in April 1987 (see 
Enlargement
). Accession talks began in October 2005. In October 2015 a Joint Action Plan was agreed between the European Commission and Turkey in order to ameliorate co-operation in responding to the migration crisis, caused, in particular, by the ongoing civil conflict in Syria. In March 2016 a new agreement was reached, known as the EU-Turkey Statement, providing for the return of migrants crossing into Greek territory and considered not to be in immediate need of international protection (see 
Justice, Migration and Home Affairs
). EU-Turkey relations were strained by Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdoğan’s uncompromising stance following a coup attempt in July of that year. Members of the EP (MEPs) have adopted several non-binding resolutions urging membership negotiations to be suspended, including in July 2017, March 2019 and May 2021. Relations with the EU were further strained after Turkey suspended application of the 2016 EU-Turkey

 agreement in February 2020, announcing that it would open the passage for migrants to cross its borders with Europe (following an upsurge in fighting in Syria, which caused the deaths of more than 30 Turkish soldiers). In March 2021 the European Council indicated its readiness to re-engage with Turkey on issues including an updated customs union, the resumption of high-level dialogue and increased co-operation in managing migration. In March 2023 the European Commission announced reconstruction aid to Türkiye of €1,000m. and humanitarian aid to Syria of €108m., following devastating earthquakes in those countries in February. The EU was to provide €26m. in humanitarian aid to Türkiye in 2024, for assistance to refugees and for those affected by the earthquakes in 2023.
